  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering.  They don't directly impose laws on individuals or businesses, but they create a framework for countries to adopt their own national laws and cooperate with each other.  Here's a breakdown of the key ones:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This is one of the earliest international agreements addressing money laundering. It focuses primarily on laundering the proceeds of drug trafficking.  It requires signatory countries to criminalize money laundering related to drug offenses.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention broadens the scope of money laundering beyond drug-related offenses to include the proceeds of a wider range of serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention addresses money laundering related to corruption offenses, such as bribery and embezzlement. It emphasizes the importance of asset recovery and the repatriation of illicitly acquired assets.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is not a treaty, but an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money",
